        <p>Medium-fine is the usual starting point for V60 and medium for Kalita/Chemex. If drawdown is very slow or cups are bitter/astringent, you are probably too fine and should step coarser.</p>
      </FaqItem>
      <FaqItem question="Conical vs flat burr for pour-over: which gives better clarity?">
        <p>Flat burr grinders often produce cleaner flavor separation and higher clarity. Conical burrs usually deliver more body and forgiving sweetness. Pick based on cup preference, not forum hype.</p>
      </FaqItem>
      <FaqItem question="Manual or electric grinder: which is better for daily pour-over use?">
        <p>Manual is better for value, portability, and one-cup routines. Electric is better for speed and repeated daily brews. If you make multiple cups most mornings, electric usually wins on consistency and convenience.</p>
      </FaqItem>
      <FaqItem question="How do I reduce fines, bitterness, or sludge in pour-over cups?">
        <p>Use a grinder with stronger burr consistency, avoid ultra-fine settings, keep burrs clean, and reduce turbulence during pours. Most sludge issues come from excessive fines and stale grinder residue.</p>
      </FaqItem>
      <FaqItem question="How often should I clean and recalibrate a grinder for consistent pour-over results?">
        <p>Do quick dry brushing every few brews and deep-clean monthly. Recalibrate if your grinder supports it and grind size shifts unexpectedly after cleaning or burr wear.</p>
      </FaqItem>
    </FaqAccordion>
